    nursingActions: ["Assess menstrual bleeding patterns using pictorial blood loss assessment chart (PBAC) — score >100 indicates heavy menstrual bleeding", "Monitor hemoglobin, hematocrit, and iron stores — initiate IV iron (ferric carboxymaltose) if ferritin <30 or Hb <10 with oral intolerance", "Educate on tranexamic acid — take only during heavy bleeding days, do not combine with hormonal contraceptives containing estrogen (increased VTE risk per some guidelines)", "Monitor for side effects of high-dose progestin therapy (bloating, mood changes, breakthrough bleeding)", "Assess for signs of hemodynamic instability in acute hemorrhagic AUB (tachycardia, orthostatic hypotension)", "Educate on endometrial biopsy indications and procedure expectations", "Coordinate gynecology referral for surgical evaluation when medical management fails", "Screen all adolescents presenting with heavy menstrual bleeding for underlying coagulopathy"],
    signs: {
      left: ["Menstrual periods >7 days duration", "Soaking through pad/tampon every 1-2 hours", "Passage of clots >2.5 cm diameter", "Intermenstrual bleeding"],
      right: ["Iron-deficiency anemia (fatigue, pallor, tachycardia)", "Orthostatic hypotension (acute hemorrhage)", "Postcoital bleeding (cervical pathology)", "Postmenopausal bleeding (endometrial pathology until proven otherwise)"]
    },
    medications: [
      { name: "Tranexamic Acid", type: "Antifibrinolytic Agent", action: "Competitively inhibits plasminogen activation by binding to lysine-binding sites on plasminogen, preventing its conversion to plasmin. This stabilizes fibrin clots within the endometrium, reducing menstrual blood loss by inhibiting local fibrinolysis without systemic prothrombotic effects at therapeutic doses", sideEffects: "Nausea, diarrhea, headache, thromboembolic events (rare at recommended doses), visual disturbances (rare — discontinue and evaluate)", contra: "Active thromboembolic disease, history of VTE, concurrent use of combination hormonal contraceptives (relative contraindication per some guidelines), subarachnoid hemorrhage, acquired color vision deficiency", pearl: "1300 mg PO TID for up to 5 days per cycle. Reduces menstrual blood loss by 40-50%. Non-hormonal option for patients who cannot or prefer not to use hormonal therapy. Safe in patients with coagulopathies when combined with other hemostatic agents." },
      { name: "Levonorgestrel IUD (52 mg)", type: "Progestin-Releasing Intrauterine System", action: "Local endometrial progestin effect causes decidualization, glandular atrophy, and stromal pseudodecidual transformation. Reduces endometrial thickness, vascular density, and prostaglandin production. Suppresses endometrial VEGF expression, reducing angiogenesis", sideEffects: "Irregular bleeding (first 3-6 months), hormonal side effects (headache, breast tenderness, mood changes), ovarian cysts, expulsion", contra: "Active pelvic infection, distorted uterine cavity (large submucosal fibroids), cervical or endometrial malignancy, unexplained vaginal bleeding pending evaluation", pearl: "NICE and ACOG recommend LNG-IUD as first-line long-term treatment for heavy menstrual bleeding. Reduces menstrual blood loss by 71-95%. Provides endometrial protection in women on tamoxifen. Can be used alongside GnRH agonists for add-back endometrial protection." }
    ],
    pearls: ["PALM-COEIN is the FIGO standard classification — always systematically evaluate structural and non-structural causes", "Endometrial biopsy is mandatory for all women >45 with AUB and those <45 with risk factors for endometrial hyperplasia", "Von Willebrand disease screening should be performed in all adolescents presenting with heavy menstrual bleeding since menarche — prevalence is ~13% in this population", "Levonorgestrel IUD is superior to oral progestins, tranexamic acid, and NSAIDs for reducing menstrual blood loss", "Acute hemorrhagic AUB management: stabilize hemodynamics first, then administer IV conjugated estrogen or high-dose oral progestin — follow with transition to maintenance hormonal therapy", "Postmenopausal bleeding is endometrial cancer until proven otherwise — endometrial thickness >4 mm on TVUS warrants biopsy"],
    quiz: [
      { question: "A 38-year-old obese woman with irregular, heavy periods has an endometrial thickness of 18 mm on transvaginal ultrasound. What is the most important next step?", options: ["Prescribe combined oral contraceptive and reassess in 3 months", "Perform endometrial biopsy to rule out hyperplasia or malignancy", "Order MRI pelvis for fibroid mapping", "Prescribe tranexamic acid for symptomatic management"], correct: 1, rationale: "This patient has significant risk factors for endometrial hyperplasia/malignancy: obesity (increased peripheral estrogen from aromatization), chronic anovulation (irregular periods), and thickened endometrium (18 mm). Endometrial biopsy is essential to exclude hyperplasia with atypia or endometrial carcinoma before initiating medical management." },
      { question: "Which molecular mechanism explains why tranexamic acid reduces menstrual blood loss?", options: ["Inhibition of COX-2 reducing prostaglandin synthesis", "Competitive inhibition of plasminogen activation, preventing fibrin clot breakdown in the endometrium", "Direct vasoconstriction of spiral arterioles via endothelin-1 stimulation", "Suppression of endometrial VEGF expression reducing angiogenesis"], correct: 1, rationale: "Tranexamic acid binds to lysine-binding sites on plasminogen, preventing its conversion to plasmin by tissue plasminogen activator (tPA). This inhibits fibrinolysis locally in the endometrium, stabilizing clots and reducing menstrual blood loss by 40-50%. It does not affect prostaglandin synthesis, vasoconstriction, or angiogenesis." }
    ]
